In order to see whether there was any gender-related difference in ACE2 expression during the aging process, we compared age-associated ACE2 content between male and female rats. The results showed that there was no significant difference in ACE2 content either between young male and female rats or between middle-aged male and female rats, but a significantly higher content was found in old female rats than male (P
 < 0.05) (Fig. 4
). The content of ACE2 decreased by 67% and 78% in the lung of 24-month old female and male rats, respectively, as compared with 3-month old rats.
